          "title": "The oracle to the mountains — God addresses the land itself",
          "body": "The most jarring feature of Ezekiel 6 is its addressee. The prophet is commanded not to speak to the people but to 'set your face toward the mountains of Israel and prophesy against them' (6:2). The mountains, hills, ravines, and valleys are summoned as defendants in a covenant lawsuit. This is not poetic personification for its own sake — it is a legal and theological move. The land had been defiled by the worship conducted on it (Lev. 18:25, 28; Num. 35:34), and the land will bear the covenant consequences of that defilement. The divine voice ranges across the entire topography of Israel precisely because Israel had colonized every feature of that topography for idolatrous use: 'every high hill, all the tops of the mountains, under every green tree and under every leafy oak' (6:13). By addressing the mountains, God announces that the coming judgment will be as geographically comprehensive as the sin that provoked it."
