          "title": "The anatomy of judgment — altars, idols, and the slain",
          "body": "The judgment oracle of 6:3-7 works by systematic inversion. The infrastructure Israel built for worship becomes the site of Israel's death. High places are destroyed (6:3). Altars are desolated (6:4). Incense altars are smashed (6:4, 6). Then the worshipers themselves fall — and where do they fall? 'In front of your idols' (6:4), with bones scattered 'around your altars' (6:5). The irony is pointed and purposive: the idols that could not save their worshipers now receive their corpses. The gods are exposed as powerless at the very moment their devotees needed them. This is the logic of Leviticus 26:30 enacted: 'I will destroy your high places... I will lay your dead bodies on the lifeless forms of your idols.' What Israel would not receive as warning from the prophets, they will receive as verdict from history. Daniel Block (NICOT) notes that the placement of bodies before the idols is not accidental cruelty but theological demonstration: the idol's 'protection' was fiction, and the corpses prove it."
