          "title": "Divine pathos — 'I have been hurt by their adulterous hearts'",
          "body": "Verse 9 contains one of the most theologically weighty phrases in Ezekiel: 'I have been hurt by their adulterous hearts which turned away from Me.' The verb shavar here does not mean broken in defeat — it means grieved, crushed, heartbroken. The marriage metaphor that drives Ezekiel 16 and 23 is compressed into a single clause: Yahweh is the wronged husband, and the offense has registered as personal pain. This is what the Reformed tradition calls divine pathos — not the passibility debate of classical theism, but the Biblical witness that God enters genuinely into relation with His covenant people and that their betrayal has a personal cost to Him. Jeremiah uses the same marriage-betrayal language (Jer. 3:1-5; 31:32); Hosea builds an entire book on it (Hos. 1-3). For Ezekiel, the statement functions as the emotional center of the indictment: Israel's sin was not merely ritual error or legal violation — it was the abandonment of a relationship. The judgment, therefore, is not cold machinery; it is the response of a God who loved."
