        "body": "The chapter's third movement opens with a jarring divine command to the prophet himself. Ezekiel is told to clap his hand, stamp his foot, and cry 'Alas!' — to perform grief through his own body before the watching community. This is consistent with the sign-act tradition that runs throughout Ezekiel (the clay tablet siege in ch. 4, the hair distribution in ch. 5, the baggage-packing in ch. 12, the refusal to mourn in ch. 24). The prophet's body is the primary instrument of his proclamation. What he enacts, the community must watch; what he performs, they cannot easily ignore.\n\nThe three-fold death formula of verse 12 — plague for those far off, sword for those nearby, famine for those besieged — is Ezekiel's characteristic triple threat, appearing also in 5:12 and rooted in the covenant curse-sequence of Leviticus 26:25-26 and Deuteronomy 28:21-22. The triad is comprehensive by design: sword, famine, and plague (*cherev, raav, dever*) are the three arms of ancient siege-warfare, and together they cover every population category. No geographic position offers escape — distant, near, or besieged inside a city. The phrase 'I will spend My wrath on them' uses the verb *kalah* (to complete, to exhaust), suggesting that the divine anger is not open-ended but measured toward its full execution.\n\nThe emotional force of this passage is significant. The prophet is not commanded to deliver the oracle with judicial detachment; he is commanded to grieve. This aligns with Ezekiel's own lament tradition (cf. the lamentation-poems of chs. 19, 26, 27, 28, 32) and with the character of the God who, in 6:9, 'has been hurt.' Judgment in Ezekiel is never celebrated; it is performed in sorrow, as an unwanted necessity forced by unrepentant idolatry.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Nakhah* (clap) and *raqa* (stamp) are physical-action verbs; *ach* is the lament-interjection 'alas, woe.' *Cherev, raav, dever* — sword, famine, plague — are the covenant-curse triad of Lev. 26 and Deut. 28. *Kalah chemah* (spend/exhaust wrath) — the same idiom at Ezek. 13:15; 20:8, 21; the wrath is finite and purposive, not arbitrary."
